<span id="freeTextContainer3227574215994998179">Finished this book last night. I was eager to see how it resolved and kept reading waiting to get to that point. But I have to say that I grew confused and tired of all of the reverses in the apparent characters of the individuals involved in the story. I have to say that this family had some sick puppies in it! I don&apos;t know, in the end, I just didn&apos;t feel a lot for any of them, particularly when Genevieve revealed what she did in the end. What did I learn from this book? I&apos;m not certain - maybe</span>
  <span id="freeText3227574215994998179" style="display:none">Finished this book last night. I was eager to see how it resolved and kept reading waiting to get to that point. But I have to say that I grew confused and tired of all of the reverses in the apparent characters of the individuals involved in the story. I have to say that this family had some sick puppies in it! I don't know, in the end, I just didn't feel a lot for any of them, particularly when Genevieve revealed what she did in the end. What did I learn from this book? I'm not certain - maybe that all of us are flawed and have the capacity to do terrible things to each other? Who was the villain? Was there one? We didn't get to know Sebastian's or Jack's viewpoint, so perhaps they would have been just as flawed and self-serving as the rest of them, had we heard their voices. I can't say that I would recommend this book, because it just did not have anything uplifting to say (imo). </span>
